4. COPYLEFT AND SOURCE CODE REQUIREMENTS

(a) Distribution of Covered Works. If Licensee distributes, publishes, conveys, sells, sublicenses, or otherwise makes available a Covered Work to any third party, Licensee must license the entire Covered Work under this Agreement and provide the complete Corresponding Source in a publicly accessible manner.

(b) Network Use. If Licensee modifies the Work and allows users to interact with the Modified Work remotely through a network, including through SaaS, APIs, hosted services, web applications, mobile backends, or similar services, Licensee must make the complete Corresponding Source of the Modified Work publicly accessible to those users under this Agreement.

(c) No Additional Restrictions. Licensee may not impose legal, contractual, technical, or technological restrictions that prevent recipients from exercising the rights granted under this Agreement.

(d) Mere Aggregation. Mere aggregation of the Work with separate and independent works on the same storage medium, repository, package manager, container image, distribution system, or platform does not by itself cause such separate works to become Covered Works.

(e) Communication With Separate Programs. A separate program does not become a Covered Work solely because it communicates with the Work through standard input/output, command-line invocation, network protocols, inter-process communication, plugins, documented APIs, or other ordinary mechanisms, unless such combination creates a derivative work under applicable law.


---

5. ATTRIBUTION, PROVENANCE, AND TRACEABILITY

(a) Preservation of Notices. Licensee must preserve all copyright notices, license notices, attribution notices, source repository references, and traceability notices included in the Work or generated by the Work, except where removal is strictly necessary for legal compliance, security, or privacy protection.

(b) Attribution in Source Distributions. Any distribution of the Work or a Covered Work in source form must include a copy of this Agreement and an Attribution Notice in a customary location, such as a LICENSE, NOTICE, AUTHORS, README, or equivalent file.

(c) Attribution in Binary or Hosted Use. Any distribution, deployment, or hosted use of a Covered Work must provide an Attribution Notice in a reasonable and customary location, such as product documentation, an about page, legal notices page, API metadata endpoint, command-line help output, package metadata, application settings page, or other location reasonably accessible to users.

(d) Attribution in Output Files. If Licensee publishes, distributes, or makes externally available Output files generated directly by the Work or a Covered Work, Licensee must include a reasonable Attribution Notice in or with such Output files where technically feasible, customary for the relevant medium, and not materially burdensome. This may be satisfied through embedded metadata, file headers, footers, comments, accompanying notice files, documentation, manifests, sidecar files, API metadata, model cards, dataset cards, SPDX metadata, or another customary and reasonably accessible method.

(e) Suggested Output Attribution Form. Unless the Project provides a different attribution format, the following form is sufficient:

> Generated using or with the assistance of [Project Name], available at [Repository URL], licensed under the Traceable Provenance Open License (TPOL) 0.9 Draft.



(f) No False Endorsement. Attribution must not imply that Licensor, the Project, or the Project Maintainer endorses Licensee, Licensee's products, or Licensee's Output, unless separately agreed in writing.

(g) Machine-Readable Provenance. Where technically feasible and customary for the relevant ecosystem, Licensee should preserve or provide machine-readable provenance and traceability metadata associated with the Work or Covered Work, including SPDX identifiers, cryptographic signatures, build provenance, source repository references, model cards, dataset cards, software bills of materials (SBOMs), or equivalent metadata.

(h) Integrity of Traceability Information. Licensee must not intentionally falsify, forge, or materially misrepresent provenance, attribution, authorship, repository origin, cryptographic signatures, trace manifests, or machine-readable traceability metadata associated with the Work or a Covered Work.

(i) AI and Machine Learning Systems.

For machine learning and generative AI systems:

1. Model weights, checkpoints, adapters, LoRA modules, embeddings, or similar artifacts generated using the Work are considered Output unless they themselves contain copyrighted portions of the Work.


2. Training data, prompts, user inputs, and fine-tuning datasets supplied by Licensee remain Licensee Input.


3. Inference outputs generated from Licensee Input are not considered derivative works of the Work solely because they were generated using the Work.


4. Where technically feasible, Licensee should preserve provenance metadata describing model origin, training source references, fine-tuning lineage, or generation pipeline information.


5. Model cards, dataset cards, or equivalent transparency documentation are encouraged for public deployments of Covered Works involving machine learning systems.




